"SECTION3_PARAGRAPH2" = "When a measurement is out of range, it’s called an outlier. Typically, most of your measurements will be in range and you’ll have no outliers. That’s a sign that things are likely consistent.";
"VIEW_TITLE" = "Vitals Article";
"SECTION2_TITLE" = "What kinds of factors can affect these measurements?";
"ARTICLE_DESCRIPTION" = "Certain metrics can give you a sense of how your body is doing.";
"SECTION4_TITLE" = "How to use this information";
"SECTION2_PARAGRAPH1" = "Many factors can cause an increase or a decrease in your metrics. A common one is getting sick. Take heart rate for example. If you catch a cold, your heart often beats faster while you sleep to help your body fight off the infection. Your heart rate will be higher when you sleep.";
"ARTICLE_TITLE" = "Understanding Your Vitals";
"SECTION1_PARAGRAPH1" = "If you’ve heard the term vitals before, it was likely in the doctor’s office when they checked your vital signs. Vital signs are a set of very specific measurements—such as heart rate and temperature—doctors use to get an essential view into your overall health. ";
"SECTION3_PARAGRAPH1" = "Because you’re looking for short term changes in these metrics, it can be helpful to compare your measurement from last night to recent averages. The recent averages can give you a baseline range to compare the recent measurement against.";
"SECTION4_PARAGRAPH1" = "Knowing when one or more metrics are out of range can help you reflect on any recent changes in your lifestyle or environment, and in some cases, make decisions about what to do next. An athlete might take a recovery day if their resting heart rate is high after a big training session. Someone might prioritize rest after traveling to higher elevation if their blood oxygen is low and their respiratory rate is high.";
"SECTION1_PARAGRAPH2" = "Outside the doctor’s office, people are using wearable devices that take more frequent measurements of even more metrics.  With the right set and frequency of measurements, people are able to get a sense of how they’re doing from day to day. It’s often best to measure these metrics at night because that provides the most consistent, comparable data. If you wear Apple Watch to sleep, it can track these metrics for you. ";
"SECTION2_PARAGRAPH2" = "Factors can be something you’ve done or something in your environment. Things like drinking alcohol, recovering from exercise, as well as hormonal changes related to the menstrual cycle can bring your heart rate up. For each measurement, a unique set of factors can cause an increase or a decrease. Sometimes, there will be multiple factors causing a change.";
"SECTION4_PARAGRAPH2" = "It’s possible to have outliers and no symptoms. If several metrics are out of range, you can check the Vitals app to get a better idea of all the different factors that could be contributing to these changes.";
"SECTION3_TITLE" = "When to pay attention to a change";
"SECTION1_PARAGRAPH3" = "We all know what it’s like to wake up and feel a little off. Metrics like heart rate, respiratory rate, and wrist temperature can help you get a sense for why, because they often change when there’s something worth paying attention to. ";
"SECTION4_PARAGRAPH3" = "Vitals is not designed to detect illness or a medical condition. If you’re concerned about a change in your health, you should speak with a doctor.";
